]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year old retired farmer comes in for a routine skin check. He complains of an increasing number of raised, \u201cwart-like\u201d lesions on his back (Image). He has noticed them appearing over the past 10 years or so. When asked, the patient says he has not noticed any pain, itching, or bleeding from these lesions, and they are not changing rapidly over time. He otherwise feels well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of diveritculitis and gastro-oesophageal reflux. His medications include omeprazole. He has no history of burns, organ transplant, or immunosuppression. As a farmer he always wore sun protection. He has no family history of any type of cancer. He is a non-smoker and he drinks two glasses of wine on the weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis for the pictured starred lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Solar keratosis (actinic keratosis)","Seborrhoeic keratosis","Melanoma","Lentigo maligna","Dysplastic naevi"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThese are most likely \u003Cstrong\u003Eseborrhoeic keratoses\u003C/strong\u003E, with a typical raised, wart-like surface and stuck-on appearance. Though benign, they may be removed with cryotherapy, shave or excision biopsy for cosmetic reasons.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOccasionally \u003Cstrong\u003Emelanoma\u003C/strong\u003E can develop within a seborrhoeic keratosis; however, this is far less likely the case in this patient, given the lesion does not have multiple colours, is not rapidly changing, bleeding, itchy, and is not irregularly bordered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELentigo maligna\u003C/strong\u003E is also known as Hutchinson\u2019s melanocytic freckle, which presents as a single slowly changing patch of discoloured skin. At first, this often resembles a freckle, but over a long period of time grows in size to be \u0026gt;6mm, and develops an irregular shape with variable pigmentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESolar keratosis (or actinic keratosis)\u003C/strong\u003E are rough scaly patches of skin that present on areas that have been exposed to the sun (such as the forehead or face). They are thick scaly growths which develop in varying sizes, often with a scaly yellow-white crust at the top.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysplastic naevi\u003C/strong\u003E are moles that are irregular in shape and larger than the average mole. They also have several colours on the mole, with an irregular surface. Despite these characteristics, dysplastic naevi rarely progress to malignant melanoma. Patients with a large number of naevi (50-100) are at increased risk (5 to 17 times) of one developing into a melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Seborrheic keratoses are benign skin tumours that have a typical raised, wart-like surface and stuck-on appearance."],"references":["Greco MJ, Bhutta BS. Seborrheic Keratosis. In: StatPearls [Internet].  2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545285/","Clarke P. Benign pigmented skin lesions. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2019;48:364-7. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/june/benign-pigmented-skin-lesions"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26525"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1595"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1683"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1683"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8c6c20a2-db86-40ff-8cd3-5736de9d350f.jpg","thumbUrl